# gen149: inline code debugging — mod_code module.
# Basic checks: missing semicolons, type mismatches, unclosed strings,
# unbalanced braces/parens, unknown functions, language identification.
# The module is grounded in kb/coding.p0; these tests prove the
# behaviour emerges from the KB, not from hardcoded strings.

# --- missing semicolon (declaration without ;) ---
> what is wrong with this code: int x = 5
< Issue found: Missing semicolon at the end of a statement.

# --- missing semicolon (return without ; before }) ---
> what is wrong with this code: int main() { return 0 }
< Issue found: Missing semicolon at the end of a statement.

# --- type mismatch (string assigned to int) ---
> what is wrong with this code: int x = "hello";
< Issue found: Type mismatch: a string is assigned to an int variable. Use char * or char[] for strings.

# --- language identification: C ---
> what language is this code: int main(void) { return 0; }
< This looks like C code.

# --- language identification: Python ---
> what language is this code: def foo(): pass
< This looks like Python code.

# --- fix suggestion (for a missing-semicolon case) ---
> fix this code: int x = "hello"
< Fix: add a semicolon at the end of each statement.

# --- valid code ---
> is this valid C: int x = 5;
< This code looks valid at first glance (basic syntax checks pass).

# --- explain code ---
> explain this code: printf("hello");
< This is a C code snippet. It prints output using printf.

# --- gen322: CORRECT code must produce NO finding (the contract nobody sealed) ---
# Every case above feeds the checkers BROKEN code, so nothing ever proved they
# stay SILENT. They did not: the missing-semicolon check compared the character
# immediately before '}' — a SPACE in a one-line function — so every correct
# one-line C function was reported "Missing semicolon at the end of a statement."
# A checker is only trustworthy once it has been shown to say nothing.
# The claim is now grounded in the compiler that was already in the tree: if
# cc -fsyntax-only accepts the translation unit, a syntax finding is false by
# construction.
> what is wrong with this code: int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.

# The whitespace pair that localizes the old bug exactly: these two differ by ONE
# SPACE, and used to get opposite verdicts.
> what is wrong with this code: int f(void) { return 0; }
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.
> what is wrong with this code: int f(void) { return 0;}
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.

# Held-out shapes: a loop, a call, a pointer, multiple statements.
> find the bug in: int sum(int n) { int s = 0; for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) s += i; return s; }
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.
> what is wrong with this code: void swap(int *a, int *b) { int t = *a; *a = *b; *b = t; }
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.

# HONESTY: this one really IS wrong (i <= n sums 1..n, not 1..n-1), and parrot0
# cannot see a SEMANTIC bug. It must say what it checked and stop — never invent
# a syntax defect to look useful. A misclaim is worse than a wall.
> what is wrong with this code: int sum(int n) { int s = 0; for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) s += i; return s; }
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.
